  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards and frameworks\n\n2. Legal Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual Legal Assistance Treaties (MLATs)\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Extradition agreements\n- Cross-border investigative collaboration\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Consistent customer due diligence protocols\n- Comparable suspicious transaction monitoring\n- Aligned anti-money laundering (AML) definitions\n\n4. Enforcement Coordination\n- Joint international investigations\n- Synchronized financial sanctions\n- Coordinated asset seizure and recovery\n- Multilateral prosecution efforts\n\n5. Compliance Frameworks\n- Global banking regulations\n- International banking standards\n- Transnational financial disclosure requirements\n- Unified risk assessment protocols\n\n6. Technological Integration\n- Shared digital platforms\n- International financial intelligence networks\n- Cross-border transaction monitoring systems\n- Enhanced digital forensic capabilities\n\nThese intersections create comprehensive, multilayered approaches to combating complex money laundering activities across national boundaries.",
